<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministry Says Ukraine Asking Too Much for Bombers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Ministry Says Ukraine Asking Too Much for Bombers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1705163294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1436 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1705163294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 17 TASS -- Ukraine is ready to sell 42 
strategic bombers which it inherited from the former Soviet 
Union to Russia, but claims eight billion U.S. dollars for them 
(15 trillion roubles), while Russia believes 217 billion roubles 
are enough. 
  Although Russia needs the planes it will not pay such a 
price 
for them. "If Ukraine does not agree to our terms the planes 
will remain on its territory," Liutenant-General Yuriy Merkulov 
from the Defence Ministry told TASS. 
  Military experts told TASS on Tuesday that Russia needs the 
bombers as they are not liable to reduction under the START I 
Treaty. They will be decommissioned only after their service 
time expires. 
  At present the Russian Air Force has 77 heavy bombers and it 
is hard to build new ones because of financial difficulties. No 
changes are planned by the Defence Ministry regarding the number 
of bombers. 
  Defence Ministry sources also told TASS that Russian 
estimates were made in 1993 prices and took into account 
ammortization costs, but Ukraine objected to such an approach. 
  At the same time Kiev has no money and technical 
possibilities to maintain the bombers in proper order by itself. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

