<H3> <TI>   Gen. Sergeyev Cited on Compliance With START I Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gen. Sergeyev Cited on Compliance With START I Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0605073094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 6 May 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> MK0605073094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS report: "Russia Implements START-1 Accord and </F>
Helps Ukraine, Kazakhstan, and Belorussia to Become Non-Nuclear"] 
  [Text] From the moment the START I accord on the reduction 
of offensive weapons went into effect, Russia "has destroyed 350 
missiles and 300 launchers," Colonel General Igor Sergeyev, 
commander in chief of the Strategic Rocket Forces, told a press 
conference. He reminded the audience that Ukraine, Kazakhstan, 
and Belorussia [Belarus] became parties to this accord in June 
1992, and this put a fresh obligation upon Russia. 
  For example, according to Gen. Sergeyev, 180 nuclear weapons 
have been shipped from Ukraine to the Russian Federation to be 
destroyed at Russian plants under agreements between both 
countries and the United States. Besides, as the commander in 
chief intimated, as of last year Ukraine removed from alert 
status RS-18 missile systems with expired guarantee dates; the 
shipping of nuclear weapons to the Russian Federation and the 
radiological decontamination of SS-24 missiles began this year. 
  Gen. Sergeyev also recalled that, in line with an agreement 
signed with Minsk, the Strategic Rocket Forces group has been 
placed under Moscow's jurisdiction: A scheduled withdrawal of 
missile regiments to Russian territory is in progress. 
  An agreement also was reached this March with Kazakhstan on 
lending a "Russian status" to the missile subunits deployed in 
the republic, and on the dates for their pullout. Now an 
agreement is in the works of the elimination of the missile 
systems. 
  Col. Gen. Sergeyev underscored that the implementation of 
the 
disarmament process depends not only on the United States and 
the Russian Federation but also on all former Soviet republics 
on whose territories strategic arms are deployed. 

</TEXT>

