<F P=100> EAST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Willingness To Sign Chemical Weapons Convention Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Willingness To Sign Chemical Weapons Convention Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2604200994 Sofia BTA in English 1757 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2604200994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, April 26 (BTA) -- Mr. Ian Kenyon, executive 
secretary of the preparatory commission to set up an 
Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW), 
told a news conference at the Foreign Ministry here today that 
Bulgaria has the political will to ratify within the coming 
weeks the Convention on the Prohibition of the Development, 
Production, Stockpiling and Use of Chemical Weapons and on their 
Destruction. 
  He was referring to the assurances he received this morning 
at a meeting with ranking members of the National Assembly 
Committee on National Security. 
  Mr. Kenyon said that at a meeting with military leaders of 
the General Staff he had discussed the question of Bulgaria's 
protection against a possible use of chemical weapons and the 
measures which the Bulgarian Army will take in the event of a 
threat of use of such weapons of mass destruction in a possible 
military conflict. 
  Asked by BTA whether the commission has information that any 
of the warring parties in the Yugoconflict has used chemical 
weapons, Mr. Kenyon said that he only had an information 
bulletin, according to which primitive warfare chemical agents 
like chlorine had been used in the former Yugoslavia but did not 
have evidence of the use of nerve gases. 
  These are just a couple of bulletins and not evidence, he 
emphasized. Of course, when the convention enters into force, 
inspectors will be sent there to verify the truth. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

