<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> COLOMBIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Regional Prosecutor Summons Cali Leaders </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Regional Prosecutor Summons Cali Leaders </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94WD0302B Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 16 Mar 94 
p 8A </F>

<F P=103> 94WD0302B </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] Medellin -- Gilberto Rodriguez Orejuela and Jose 
Santacruz Londono, presumed "capos" of the Cali Cartel, have 
three court days to appear for questioning before the Office of 
the Regional Prosecutor of Antioquia. This action is connected 
with the investigation of the explosion of a car bomb in front 
of the Monaco Building, owned by the late Pablo Escobar Gaviria. 
  Through a citation order posted at 0800 yesterday, in the 
prosecutors' common secretariat, the Prosecutor's Office 
summoned Rodriguez and Santacruz to submit to questioning as 
presumed intellectual perpetrators of the car bomb. Its 
explosion occurred at dawn on 13 January 1988, in front of the 
building in which the "capo" was residing with his family. 
  The citation order was posted in Medellin, Cali, and 
Mariquita, and its terms will run from the time that the 
document is posted in the two latter cities. According to 
official spokesmen, if, within the next three days, the pair 
accused of this terrorist act fail to appear for questioning, 
implementing their submission to justice, the process will 
follow its normal course and court-appointed attorneys will be 
named. 
  Killed in the attack on the Monaco Building were Miguel 
Angel 
Espinoza and Javier de Jesus Tamayo Perez, guards of the 
property. After the explosion, the authorities discovered inside 
the building a valuable art collection containing such works as 
paintings by Botero, Dali, Grau, Obregon, and Dario Morales. It 
also included one of the seven copies of Rodin's "The Thinker" 
existing in the world, Chinese vases of the Ming Dynasty, and 
pre-Columbian works. 
  Moreover, they found in the Monaco Building's basement eight 
antique vehicles, a collection of motorcycles, and a completely 
armored Mercedes-Benz limousine. 
  The explosion destroyed three nearby houses and seriously 
damaged several adjacent buildings, causing losses in the 
millions. 
  Furthermore, yesterday the authorities extended the 
questioning in the Antioquia Regional Prosecutor's Office of 
Valentin de Jesus Taborda, one of Pablo Escobar's aides, 
arrested in Itagui, and Luis Eduardo Fernandez Bedoya, alias 
"Lucho," ringleader of the people's militias in Valle de Aburra. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

