<H3> <TI>   Source Denies Involvement of Police Chief in Drug Trafficking </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Source Denies Involvement of Police Chief in Drug Trafficking </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2604004394 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1030 
GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2604004394 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A source close to the Haitian Army denies the 
accusations brought against the Haitian police chief, Lieutenant 
Colonel Joseph Michel Francois. According to the charges, the 
police chief has allegedly supported a lucrative drug trade 
between Colombia and the United States, through Haiti. Gabriel 
Taboada, a former Colombian drug trafficker, asserted before the 
[U.S. Senate] Drug Trafficking and Terrorism Subcommission that 
he met Michel Francois during a meeting with Pablo Escobar in 
(Colombia). Former Haitian President Prosper Avril also 
participated in that meeting. 
  The source, who wishes to remain anonymous, has pointed out 
that Col. Francois' last trip took place in 1981 before 
[corrects himself] after he was commissioned. He went to the 
United States for proficiency courses in security. Since then, 
he has never gone abroad. How can Taboada assert that he met 
Col. Francois in 1984, our source wonders. 
  Let us recall that upon the return of Col. Francois, he was 
appointed to the Corps of Heavy Vehicles [as heard] of the 
presidential guard at the National Palace. 

</TEXT>

