BFN 

  [Text] The spokesman for President Aristide, Jean-Claude 
Martineau, has reacted to the antidrug operation led by the 
Haitian military authorities. The initiative has come too late, 
according to the president's spokesman. Martineau has reaffirmed 
that the Haitian military authorities are involved in drug 
trafficking, up to the hilt. [begin recording, in Creole] 
  Martineau: A big drug dealer made a series of 
statements before the U.S. Senate, perhaps one week ago. He 
stated before a U.S. Senate committee that [Lieutenant Colonel] 
Michel Francois [Port-au-Prince police chief] is involved in 
drug trafficking, up to the hilt. Obviously, it was not 
necessary for anyone to come tell us about that to know it. 
Besides, this is something that President Aristide has been 
denouncing for some times. We have heard that there is an 
operation aimed at arresting drug dealers in Haiti. Why are they 
trying to arrest those involved in drug trafficking (only) after 
this accusation, when they knew about it previously? [end 
recording] 
  This was the spokesman for President Aristide, Jean-Claude 
Martineau. 

