<F P=100> NEAR EAST &amp; SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Joint Antidrug Agreement Between Pakistan, Iran </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Joint Antidrug Agreement Between Pakistan, Iran </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0605065194 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network in Urdu 0200 
GMT 6 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0605065194 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network </F>
<F P=105>  Urdu </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pakistan and Iran have agreed to make joint efforts 
with technical and financial assistance from the United Nations 
to check drug trafficking along their borders. A memorandum of 
understanding to this effect was signed in Tehran by retired 
Major General Nasirullah Khan Babar, Pakistani interior 
minister; 'Ali Mohammad Besharati-Jahromi, Iranian interior 
minister; and Giorgio Giacomelli, executive director of the UN 
International Narcotics Control Program. Under the agreement, 
antinarcotics measures along the border between the two 
countries will be made more effective, communications facilities 
will be improved, and arrangements will be made for training 
professionals of law-enforcement agencies. About $30 million 
will be spent on the new antinarcotics measures, of which $21 
million will be paid by Iran which will mostly be used for road 
construction to facilitate the speedy movement of security 
forces. Pakistan will provide $5.5 million, while the UN 
International Narcotics Control Program will pay $3.6 million. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

